<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="1813f3f0-21ab-5fd5-bd3b-977fd591d169" activityNameId="5e6bf872-5750-4516-979b-406b28e82e3a" parentActivityId="a3dec25c-883f-4071-a09a-17206728d362" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">N,N-dimethylformamide production, direct synthesis</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> HCON(CH3)2</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">DMF</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with N,N-dimethylformamide being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of n,n-dimethylformamide (DMF) based on the direct synthesis (or one-step) process. n,n-Dimethylformamide is prepared by the reaction of N,N-dimethylamine with carbon monoxide (Sutter, 2007). Two methods dominate present-day commercial preparation of DMF: direct synthesis and a two-step process. N,N-dimethylformamide is produced by a number of manufacturers worldwide; total capacity is estimated at 250 000 t per year (Ullmann 2004).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reaction in the direct synthesis process:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">CO+ HN(CH3)2 → HCON(CH3)2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">N,N-dimethylformamide (C3H7NO, CAS: 68-12-2) is a colorless, high-boiling, nonviscous, highly polar, distillable, hygroscopic liquid with a weak, characteristically amine-like odor (Ullmann, 2004). The principal applications of n,n-dimethylformamide are as a solvent and as an extractant, particularly for salts and compounds with high molecular mass. This role is consistent with its interesting combination of physical and chemical properties: low molecular mass, high dielectric constant, electron- donor characteristics, and ability to form complexes. The use of DMF as a component in synthesis is of relatively minor significance, at least commercially.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">The most important use of DMF as a solvent for polymers is in the preparation of polyacrylonitrile solutions for the manufacture of fibrous polyacrylonitrile. Residual DMF can be recovered from the spun fibers with relatively little expenditure of energy. In addition DMF is used as a solvent in the preparation of high-quality surfaces based on polyurethanes, which are otherwise difficult to solubilize, and it is employed as a solvent for coating surfaces with polyamides.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The high boiling point and high solvating power of DMF lead to its further use as a solvent for wire enamel formulated with polyamides, polyesterimides, or polyurethanes (Sutter, 2007). Conversely, its solubilizing ability also makes it an effective component of paint removers, and it is used as a selective solvent in a wide range of manufacturing processes. For example, DMF is useful in separating acetylene from ethylene; butadiene from C4 cuts; and hydrogen chloride, hydrogen sulfide, or sulfur dioxide from CO2-containing gases. N,N-Dimethylformamide or mixtures containing it are used by oil refiners to extract aromatic compounds from hydrocarbon mixtures.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Solutions of salts in specially purified DMF serve as fillers for electrolytic capacitors, a role made possible by the high dielectric constant of DMF. This substance is also used either alone or with other solvents in the recrystallization of aromatics, heterocyclics, dyes, fluorescent whitening agents, and pigments. The pharmaceutical industry also utilizes its broad solvent and extractant properties N,N-Dimethylformamide could potentially be employed in the synthesis of aldehydes, acetals, amides, amidines, esters, and heterocycles, but thus far its use has been limited.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Bipp H., Kieczka, H.: Formamides. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Sutter, Jurgen. "Life cycle inventories of petrochemical solvents." Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. Final Report Ecoinvent Data 2 (2007).</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset covers the direct synthesis process for N,N-dimethylformamide (DMF), which is produced starting from pure carbon monoxide (or a gas stream containing carbon monoxide) and N,N-dimethylamine, within a solution of alkali alkoxide (usually sodium methoxide) in methanol as catalyst (Ullmann, 2004).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">CO+ HN(CH3)2 → HCON(CH3)2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The reaction is conducted between 0.5 and 11 MPa at 50 – 200 °C. The reaction mixture exits the reactor through a decompression chamber. In addition to N,N-dimethylformamide, the crude product contains methanol, a certain amount of unreacted N,N-dimethylamine, dissolved carbon monoxide, and residual catalyst. The addition of acid or water deactivates any catalyst present, resulting in the formation of sodium formate. Dissolved carbon monoxide, together with inert gases, escapes from the mixture during decompression, and the off-gases are removed by combustion. Preliminary distillation is followed by a second distillation in a separate column; here, dimethylformamide is separated from methanol which contains traces of N,N-dimethylamine. Further distillation results in a product of 99.9 % purity.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Alternative synthesis technology:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The two steps process differs from direct synthesis because methyl formate is prepared separately and introduced in the form of ca. 96 % pure (commercial grade) material (Ullmann, 2004). Equimolar amounts of methyl formate and N,N-dimethylamine are subjected to a continuous reaction at 60 – 100 °C and 0.1 – 0.3 MPa. The resulting product is a mixture of N,N-dimethylformamide and methanol. The purification process involves distillation and is analogous to that described for direct synthesis. However, no separation of salts is required because no catalysts are involved in the process. According to the corrosive properties of both starting materials and products, stainless steel has to be used as material of construction for production facilities.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">In this dataset, a yield of 95% was assumed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Bipp H., Kieczka, H.: Formamides. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2003-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 2003) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
